Events.html: 1767 – Pitcairn Island is discovered by Midshipman Robert Pitcairn on an expeditionary voyage commanded by Philip Carteret.

Events.html: 1767 – Norway's oldest newspaper still in print, Adresseavisen, is founded and the first edition is published.

Events.html: 1778 – American Revolutionary War: British forces kill 360 people in the Wyoming Valley massacre.
Events.text: American Revolutionary War: British forces kill 360 people in the Wyoming Valley massacre.

Events.html: 1819 – The Bank of Savings in New York City, the first savings bank in the United States, opens.

Events.html: 1839 – The first state normal school in the United States, the forerunner to today's Framingham State College, opens in Lexington, Massachusetts with 3 students.

Events.html: 1844 – The last pair of Great Auks is killed.
Events.text: The last pair of Great Auks is killed.

Events.html: 1848 – Slaves are freed in the Danish West Indies (now U.S. Virgin Islands) by Peter von Scholten in the culmination of a year-long plot by enslaved Africans.

Events.html: 1849 – The French enter Rome in order to restore Pope Pius IX to power. This would prove a major obstacle to Italian unification.

Events.html: 1852 – Congress establishes the United States' 2nd mint in San Francisco.

Events.html: 1898 – Spanish–American War: The Spanish fleet, led by Pascual Cervera y Topete, is destroyed by the U.S. Navy in Santiago, Cuba.

Events.html: 1913 – Confederate veterans at the Great Reunion of 1913 reenact Pickett's Charge; upon reaching the high-water mark of the Confederacy they are met by the outstretched hands of friendship from Union survivors.

Events.html: 1940 – World War II: In order to stop the ships from falling into German hands the French fleet of the Atlantic based at Mers El Kébir, is bombarded by the British fleet, coming from Gibraltar, causing the loss of three battleships: Dunkerque, Provence and Bretagne. One thousand two hundred sailors perish.
